oader return a ByteArrayInputStream. However, since my call site relies on classPath.getResourceAsStream, which is part of the ClassLoader, I wouldn't need resource metadata here. Alternatively, I could create a custom ClassLoader that overrides getResourceAsStream to return a hardcoded byte array for a generated class with a major version of 52. This approach might work well!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering class loading options**\\n\\nI'm thinking I don't need to rely on direct reflection after all. I could use the ByteArrayClassPath class loader to override getResourceAsStream. I'll have to import ByteArrayInputStream, InputStream, and IOException for that. It seems I can copy generatedClassBytes without using reflection. The specific class name I need is \\\"cglib.cglib.ReloadedTypeForAbstractClassLoaderFixture\\\". So, no extra top-level class is needed, and I’ll remember to remove the class at the bottom.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Thinking through exceptions**\\n\\nI’m wondering if I need to have class loading results catch RuntimeExceptions. In native code, does CodeGenerationException wrap an Error? Actually, CodeGenerationException is a RuntimeException from AbstractClassLoader; it’s not for Errors. But I’m pondering whether UnsupportedFeatureError counts as an Error. Then there's the ClassWriter: can it throw TypeNotPresent? Hmm, I think I need to ensure that defined classes on the JVM repeat loads returning the same result.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Updating test resources**\\n\\nI see that the LoadedClass line gets hit for the first time but returns null, and then it returns not null on a repeat. That's good information! Now, I need to update the test resources to remove the resources block. It looks like it's time to make some edits to ensure everything functions properly. I'll get started on that update right away!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_uja8dTJmUaa1DcFMgdOKmbkv|fc_095d48dd3c7ce